<section xml:id="Isomorphisms">
  <title>Isomorphisms</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A function <m>F:\mathbb{L}_1\longrightarrow \mathbb{L}_2</m> is an <term>Isomorphism</term>
        if <m>F</m> is a linear transformation that is <m>1-1</m> and maps onto <m>\mathbb{L}_2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given that <m>T: \mathbb{R}^3 \longrightarrow \mathbb{R}^2</m> is a linear transformation such that <m>T(1,1,0) = (1,2)</m>,
        <m>T(0,0,1)=(0,-1)</m> and <m>T(0,1,0) =(2,0)</m>.
        Determine <m>T(3,3,0)</m>,
        <m>T(1,2,3)</m>, and <m>T(x,y,z)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <question>
   <p>
    Describe the problems that could occur if the set on which the linear transformation is defined is:
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          not a spanning set for <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          not linearly independent
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
   </p>
  </question>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use a system of equations to:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              write (5,4,3) as a linear combination of (1,1,1),(0,1,1) and (0,0,1)
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              write <m>5+4x +3x^2</m> as a linear combination of <m>1+x+x^2</m>,
              <m>x+x^2</m> and <m>x^2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define a linear transformation from
        <m>\mathbb{P}_3</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
        Is it 1-1?
        Is it onto?
        What is its inverse transformation?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Any n-dimensional linear space is isomorphic to <m>\mathbb{R}^{n}</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <proposition>
   <p>
      Prove any two n-dimensional linear spaces are isomorphic.
   </p>
  </proposition>
</section>